        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;">
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           Men, it has been well said,
           <strong>
            think in herds
           </strong>
           ; it will be seen that
           <strong>
            they go mad in herds
           </strong>
           , while they only recover their senses slowly, and one by one.
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         It\xe2\x80\x99s funny that those who take finance particularly seriously dismiss meme stocks.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         \xe2\x80\x9cLeave the memes to the kids,\xe2\x80\x9d they chortle during long bull runs, \xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99ll get back to doing
         <em>
          real
         </em>
         finance once the bubble bursts and the madness subsides.\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         And then the markets turn and rates go up and a war starts and crypto tanks and growth stocks tank and meme stocks
         <em>
          really
         </em>
         tank and startups will, inevitably, once they\xe2\x80\x99re forced to raise and mark-to-market, tank.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         \xe2\x80\x9cBe careful out there, there's gonna be a lot more pain.
         <strong>
          Rates
         </strong>
         will continue to rise and
         <strong>
          multiples
         </strong>
         will continue to compress and companies will need to
         <strong>
          tighten their belts
         </strong>
         and growth will slow and senior
         <strong>
          leadership will leave
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          growth will slow
         </strong>
         further and all but a few of the best startups \xe2\x80\x93 let alone crypto projects \xe2\x80\x93
         <strong>
          will die
         </strong>
         .\xe2\x80\x9d
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Which is funny because this, too, is
         <strong>
          a meme
         </strong>
         . It\xe2\x80\x99s a story that people tell each other to cut through all of the trillions of things they
         <em>
          could
         </em>
         be paying attention to. Re-telling this story is a way for people to signal that they, too, get it. That they, too, take finance seriously. That they, too, are looking forward to the separation of wheat and chaff.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The difference is, meme stock traders know they\xe2\x80\x99re trading a meme.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Now certainly, the growth bears have some math on their side. The higher the discount rate, the lower the present value. But that\xe2\x80\x99s easy. That\xe2\x80\x99s the same
         <strong>
          first-order thinking
         </strong>
         that everyone\xe2\x80\x99s agreed upon. The idea that printing has led to inflation which will lead to more hikes which will kill growth companies and risk assets is
         <strong>
          The Current Financial Thing
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         So everyone talks about rising
         <strong>
          rates
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          hyperinflation
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          war
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          food shortages
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          nuclear threats
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          supply chain issues
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          energy prices
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          IPO windows slammed shut
         </strong>
         . They create \xe2\x80\x93 and may often feel \xe2\x80\x93 fear, uncertainty, and doubt (
         <strong>
          FUD
         </strong>
         ).
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The markets are too complex for anyone to know, with the degree of confidence with which some people pretend to know, what\xe2\x80\x99s going to happen tomorrow, let alone in a week, a month, or a year. That\xe2\x80\x99s what memes are for. That\xe2\x80\x99s why people agree on The Current Financial Thing. Throw in Twitter\xe2\x80\x99s algorithmic feed, and people can come to agree with each other more strongly, more quickly than ever before.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The Current Financial Thing is a play on the I Support The Current Thing meme, which
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OwyAMhU9Tdo3AkJ8uWMxmrhERcBrUBCIw08nthzSLkRCW_GS_588awmdMh95jJnZ-Ix076oDvvCIRJlYyptE7LToYZKsezGnlxNAOzOdxToib8aumVJDtZVq9NeRj-ExwDi1bdN-Lbm6lm2eUYgbkzvZDDwom3nW8Hy5fU5zHYFHjD6YjBmSrXoj2fJNfN_iuL1Oqce1S5cbGrXaAA9RCC95tSQkD3Wnx4Vl7zOtT5RIGAa2ERwONM3IWdpbCTNJKa5vf5S0nU8RN8e0JTS5TJmNf53aWdIg0xXSuU_y1mA3Xj1CvHGvdSvB0jBjMtKK7ANDF8YNkfGLAM7AbDVV6alB9TTSAaK-DK6FWCCUEcFadXaxT4d_0Dz98ih4" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          Ben Thompson analyzes brilliantly
         </a>
         .
        </p>
