        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         On the internet, he argues, we can find many things worthy of our support, so many, in fact, that it just makes sense to \xe2\x80\x9coutsource our intuition for which events matter\xe2\x80\x9d most. There\xe2\x80\x99s only downside in supporting Putin or opposing Black Lives Matter.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Opposing The Current
         <em>
          Financial
         </em>
         Thing, however, or at least realizing that when everyone agrees that the market is going to tank, they\xe2\x80\x99re probably wrong or too late or off-timing, might hold some alpha. In fact, trading on the predictable ways that humans react in times of panic drives the most successful quantitative hedge fund of all time.
        </p>
        <h3 style="-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; color: #1a1a1a; font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;">
         <strong>
          RenTech\xe2\x80\x99s FUD Eating Algorithms
         </strong>
        </h3>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          Humans are so predictably irrational that the best-performing hedge fund in the world has outperformed the market by 1000x since 1988 in large part by trading on our fear, uncertainty, and doubt (FUD).
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          Renaissance Technologies (\xe2\x80\x9cRenTech\xe2\x80\x9d)
         </strong>
         is a quant fund founded by mathematician Jim Simons. Quant fund means that instead of people choosing which assets to buy and sell, RenTech\xe2\x80\x99s mathematicians, statisticians, physicists, and
         <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkctuwyAURL_G7GrB5RGyYFGpajdZVVW3Fo_rhMTGFuCm-fuSZFEJwaDRZUYHbysel3wz61IquW9Dva1oEl7LhLViJlvBPMRgmALNpdiTYERgWmoSyzBmxNnGydS8IVk3N0Vva1zSY4JSkORklOKjQIvM--B0kMxBcFSKoJRujnvm2i1ETB4N_mC-LQnJZE61rqXjrx28t1Wv8d6o98vcbs5O9hxLU6Xaut0FEzuudnvJNGgNckcF7_h7e-ANaAeqNvHxyQ5fl_Gg4uXwHVQ5v7y9rFcSDVAAykEzkBz2PfTB8pH5kTPruOfe97-nK3d2Y52g8xH6srkW7C_3OiSbtFS35JiOzb6c7IzTw2hIhnbOW4r1NmCybsLwpFWf0B_8hiMmzO0zwmBrQy202LVGGph80mk4JWOCMaCkJYelTaX_0D-MApYm" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
          shape rotators
         </a>
         build
         <em>
          algorithms
         </em>
         that trade assets based on the patterns they find in enormous amounts of real-time data.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         RenTech\xe2\x80\x99s original fund, the Medallion Fund, is legendary. Since inception in 1988, it has generated
         <strong>
          39% annualized returns net of fees
         </strong>
         . That\xe2\x80\x99s particularly notable because it charged
         <strong>
          5% management fees and 44% performance fees
         </strong>
         , whereas a standard fund charges 2% and 20%. Nick Maggiulli wrote a great piece going over all of the mind-blowing ways the numbers were impressive in
         <em>
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uxCAMhU8z7BqBCZnMgkU3vUbkgJOgEoj46TS3LzNZFCEsPct-vM9goTWmUx8xF_Z6pnIepAM9s6dSKLGaKU3OajHAKFX_YFb3VoxqZC5PSyLa0XldUiV21Nk7g8XF8J7gHBTb9B35rJSCYX6AGjgIGJVY-nashWHkly9W6ygY0vRD6YyBmNdbKUe-yc8bfLUbFxu9x5QxWIsFOxP3Ju9k0fvm-bHUYJvAnAYOwCWMApSERwedRbkIs0iBszTSmO53e8oZq7j1fF-hy3XOBc33aydLOsQyx-TC2trfG-7k340WcGp1r8GVc6KAsyd7ZS8XwjeNaaVAqaG1E5YGrh_7e_vRCEJdWRscJUQvBHDWnG1sU-Hf9A99WIim" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           Of Dollars and Data
          </a>
         </em>
         , like the fact that
         <strong>
          $1 invested in 1988 would be worth $19,518 in 2018
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
