        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         So how does RenTech do it?
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The heart of the Medallion Fund\xe2\x80\x99s strategy is to bet on
         <strong>
          mean reversion
         </strong>
         \xe2\x80\x93 the idea that prices come back to their long-term average trend after asset prices get out of whack.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But how and why do prices get out of whack in such a way that the algorithms have been able to consistently take advantage of them for over thirty years? Medallion researcher Kresimir Penavic gave a simple explanation that\xe2\x80\x99s stuck with me since reading it:
        </p>
        <blockquote style="border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1em 0;">
         <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;">
          <em>
           What you\xe2\x80\x99re really modeling is
           <strong>
            human behavior
           </strong>
           \xe2\x80\xa6 Humans are most predictable in times of high stress \xe2\x80\x94
           <strong>
            they act instinctively and panic
           </strong>
           .
           <strong>
            Our entire premise was that human actors will react the way humans did in the past
           </strong>
           \xe2\x80\xa6 we learned to take advantage.
          </em>
         </p>
        </blockquote>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The most successful 30+ year run in the history of finance essentially boils down to efficiently trading the fact that humans are, as Duke econ professor Dan Ariely would say,
         <strong>
          <a href="https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM1uwyAQhJ8m3GLxZ5ccOFRqK_VW9QWsBTYJig0W4Lru03ebHCqhBe1oNMPnoeEll90uuTb2N8a2L2gTbnXC1rCwtWIZY7BikEb1-sSC1UGY3rBYx3NBnCFOtpUV2bK6KXpoMae7g3PZs6vV0GsuQJycCcoMg9a9GpxHGUAZ4fgjF9YQMXm0-IVlzwnZZK-tLfWgng_yjc62bR3M8JNT5_NMi4-CIfoGbtqP76Xcg2E6fuJXrBiOr98LpECPF_SxklbJExYanA9C9Upq-oSVXEqupBGSNqdOdlTrLPxZCXDKK--77-umHKzioPl8kV1dXW3gb38tWLEpN5dLTBeSb1eYcboLBGOke15TbPuIiVpieHBqD9x3cuMFE1J1DCM0gqyNfqJGRor-wYVA9kJoISRnlBwyudJ_6C_yA5eg" rel="" style="color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">
           predictably irrational
          </a>
          ,
         </strong>
         particularly when we\xe2\x80\x99re scared.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         In that sense, Medallion is kind of a mirror turned on humanity, existing as an abstraction layer above our petty day-to-day actions. Its returns can be viewed as almost an
         <strong>
          index of how predictably irrational humans are
         </strong>
         at any given time, and how easy it is for the robots to take advantage of our silly human emotion.
         <strong>
         </strong>
         Want to guess its three best years?
        </p>
