        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         That headline is meant to drive
         <strong>
          fear, uncertainty, and doubt
         </strong>
         . \xe2\x80\x9cWill
         <em>
          I
         </em>
         survive?!\xe2\x80\x9d it dares the reader to ask. Read on, and Linette Lopez quotes a series of
         <strong>
          value investors
         </strong>
         and
         <strong>
          short-sellers
         </strong>
         \xe2\x80\x93 the group of people most desperate for a crash \xe2\x80\x93 and holds up their word as gospel. The article doesn\xe2\x80\x99t
         <em>
          wonder
         </em>
         if, maybe, there might be a sustained pullback, but declares confidently that we\xe2\x80\x99re going to have a
         <strong>
          washout
         </strong>
         , and that there will be few survivors. FUD.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         This is Insider. It\xe2\x80\x99s known to be a little sensationalist. But it\xe2\x80\x99s also a perfect, cartoonish encapsulation of the mood more broadly.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Everyone seems to be certain about how things are going to play out, and it\xe2\x80\x99s going to be bad. Many of the people out there yelling about a market decline and return to responsible valuation are those who would benefit from either:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin-top: 0;">
         <li style="margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">
           A market pullback, or
          </p>
         </li>
         <li style="margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px; mso-special-format: bullet;">
          <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">
           A
           <em>
            perception
           </em>
           among investors that they\xe2\x80\x99re the experienced, responsible ones in a sea of crazy intemperate gamblers who\xe2\x80\x99ve been getting away with murder.
          </p>
         </li>
        </ul>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         Now I fully recognize my own biases, too. I\xe2\x80\x99ve deployed venture money for the first time during this post-COVID bull run, am long crypto, and am generally bullish and optimistic on technology. I would stand to benefit financially and reputationally from prices continuing to go up. I even believe that reading about tech companies is less exciting for people in a bear market (unless I pull a heel turn and start writing salacious stories about companies crashing, which I won\xe2\x80\x99t), so
         <strong>
          Not Boring and I would benefit from the market partying like it was 2020 every year.
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         But I\xe2\x80\x99m the first to admit
         <strong>
          I have no idea what\xe2\x80\x99s going to happen.
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         During the bull run, there seemed to be a constant chorus of bears arguing that prices would come back down to earth; this bear market (a pullback of more than 20%) seems to be a lot more one-sided.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         That\xe2\x80\x99s not to say that bears are wrong. In fact, I wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t be surprised if they\xe2\x80\x99re all right and everything goes back to selling off after this little bear rally.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         I just also wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t be surprised if the market bounces back and keeps growing.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The only thing I\xe2\x80\x99m pretty sure about is that
         <strong>
          large groups of people all agreeing about something as complex and dynamic as the market are almost always wrong
         </strong>
         .
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         The general bearish certainty feels like the kind of signal that Medallion would feed on. Abstract away all of the underlying stuff and just look at how the humans are behaving.
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         With everyone agreeing on a sustained crash, predicting the opposite was
         <strong>
          so simple a human could do it
         </strong>
         . On
         <strong>
          March 15th, at 10:52am ET
         </strong>
         , a friend who wishes not to be named texted:
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         <strong>
          \xe2\x80\x9cI also think we\xe2\x80\x99re nearing a bottom. Just based on the amount of midwit tourists prognosticating about impending doom.\xe2\x80\x9d
         </strong>
        </p>
        <p style="color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">
         He called the local bottom almost down to the hour.
        </p>
